<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-455-338  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 455 338.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Digital Review  July 24 1989 v6 n29 p4(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>MTI offers removable drives for Unix. (Micro Technology Inc.)andO;(product announcement)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Kovsky, Steven.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Micro-Technology Inc. (product introduction).andO;Product:   Micro Technology MDW (Disk drive) (product introduction)Micro Technology MDS (Disk drive) (product introduction).andO;Topic:     Product IntroductionWinchester DiskDisk DrivesSmall Computer Systems InterfaceVMEbus.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>MTI Offers Removable Drives for UnixandM;ANAHEIM, Calif.andP;  -- Micro Technology has developed two removable Winchesterdisk drive subsystems for the SCSI and VME bus controllers used in Unix-basedsystems from DEC, Sun Microsystems and Solbourne Computer.andM;The MDW-series subsystem is designed to plug into existing SCSI ports on Unixworkstations from DEC and Sun.andP;  The MDS-series subsystem is a VME bus-basedproduct for Sun and Solbourne file servers, said Micro Technology MarketingDirector Tom Raimondi.andM;He said the MDW-series uses an internal ESDI-to-SCSI converter.andM;&quot;We're finding [it] to be interchangeable with SCSI ports on the DEC, Sun andSolbourne machines,&quot; Raimondi said.andM;Many Sun machines and all Solbourne systems are equipped with both a SCSI anda VME bus peripheral connection, he said.andM;The subsystems use the same media as Micro Technology's existing removablestorage devices for HSC and SMD controller environments, said MicroTechnology President Steve Hamerslag.andM;&quot;Using this universal approach allows end users ...andP;  to migrate their storageto whichever CPU architecture makes the most sense, without forfeiting theirmass storage investment,&quot; Hamerslag said.andM;Bob Goetz, Micro Technology's vice president of sales and marketing, saidthat in addition to serving its mainstream customer base of DEC end users ingovernment and defense industries, the company also plans to market thesubsystems to computer OEMs.andM;The base price for an MDW-series subsystem is $17,000 for a two-drive unit.andO;A dual-drive MDS-series device begins at $19,000.andP;  The subsystems areavailable now, Goetz said.andM;For more information, Micro Technology Inc. can be contacted at 5065 E.andO;Hunter Ave., Anaheim, CA 92807, (714) 970-5413.andO;</TEXT></DOC>